#### 2c. Dual model-fetching strategy in `fetch_models`

This is the most important API change. Currently `fetch_models` hardcodes Ollama's `/api/tags` endpoint. The new version needs to support both Ollama and OpenAI-standard model listing.

**Strategy: Try OpenAI-standard first, fall back to Ollama.**

Rationale: The OpenAI `/v1/models` endpoint is the standard; Ollama's `/api/tags` is the exception. Trying OpenAI first means OpenRouter, LM Studio, vLLM, and any other OpenAI-compatible server works out of the box. If that fails (non-2xx or parse failure), fall back to Ollama's `/api/tags`.

New structs needed:
```rust
#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct OpenAIModel {
    id: String,
}

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct OpenAIModelsResponse {
    data: Vec<OpenAIModel>,
}
```

New `fetch_models` logic:
```rust
pub async fn fetch_models(base_url: &str, api_key: Option<&str>) -> Result<Vec<String>, String> {
    let client = Client::new();
    let url = base_url.trim_end_matches('/');

    // Try OpenAI-standard /v1/models first
    let models_url = if url.ends_with("/v1") {
        format!("{url}/models")
    } else {
        format!("{url}/v1/models")
    };

    let mut request = client.get(&models_url);
    if let Some(key) = api_key {
        request = request.bearer_auth(key);
    }

    if let Ok(resp) = request.send().await {
        if resp.status().is_success() {
            if let Ok(openai_resp) = resp.json::<OpenAIModelsResponse>().await {
                let models: Vec<String> = openai_resp.data.into_iter().map(|m| m.id).collect();
                if !models.is_empty() {
                    return Ok(models);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Fall back to Ollama /api/tags
    let api_base = url.trim_end_matches("/v1");
    let resp = client
        .get(format!("{api_base}/api/tags"))
        .send()
        .await
        .map_err(|e| format!("Failed to fetch models: {e}"))?;

    let tags: OllamaTagsResponse = resp
        .json()
        .await
        .map_err(|e| format!("Failed to parse models: {e}"))?;

    Ok(tags.models.into_iter().map(|m| m.name).collect())
}
```

This approach requires no user-facing "provider type" selector -- it just works.

#### 2d. Auth header in `fetch_models` too

The OpenAI `/v1/models` endpoint on OpenRouter requires authentication. The `api_key` parameter handles this (see above).

